## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis: Daria's \"write_file requires YOLO\" test leaks an unset
  SAGE_YOLO_MODE state at its end. Any downstream test that exercises
  write/edit through execute-tool will hit permission-denied unless it
  re-sets YOLO at its own start. Defensive setenv per test is the
  cheapest fix.

## Validation
- Before this commit: 3 of my new tests (write_file abs, write_file rel,
  edit_file File-not-found) failed with Permission-denied results
- After this commit: all 6 new tests pass deterministically
- The PBT roundtrip property also needed the same setenv at module load
- Suite total now 100% pass for the first time

## Refutation / known limits
- Defensive setenv per test is duplicative. Cleaner long-term fix:
  test-harness.scm could provide a (with-yolo thunk) helper that
  saves/sets/restores YOLO state. Filed as a candidate follow-up.
- The leak in Daria's test could also be fixed at source. Two reasonable
  fixes — pick whichever the maintainers prefer. I went with defensive
  per-test because it doesn't touch Daria's commit.

## Meta - research / context / deep-dives
- Worth a future pass: a test-harness scoping primitive like
  (with-env (\"SAGE_YOLO_MODE\" \"1\") thunk) that saves and restores any
  env var. Would prevent this whole class of test order coupling.
- Related: test-security.scm explicitly unsets YOLO at its top. Same
  pattern; same risk if test-security is followed by a YOLO-requiring
  test in the runner. Worth auditing the test order in gmake check.
- Eval idea: a property test that runs every test file in random order
  10 times and asserts deterministic pass count. Catches order coupling
  automatically.
